# SwiftUI 6 App Rules

Use these rules when creating or modifying SwiftUI app code.

## Modern SwiftUI

- Prefer `@Observable` over `ObservableObject` for new shared state.
- Use `@State` for view-owned state.
- Mark `@State` properties `private`.
- Use `@Binding` only when a child view must modify parent state.
- Use `@Bindable` when an injected observable model needs bindings.
- Keep view `body` pure: no side effects, no blocking work, no heavy computation.
- Move business logic into testable model/service types instead of embedding it in views.

## Navigation and Presentation

- Use `NavigationStack`, not `NavigationView`.
- Use `navigationDestination(for:)` for type-safe navigation.
- Prefer `.sheet(item:)` for model-driven sheets.
- Sheets should own their dismiss action through `dismiss()`.
- Avoid global singleton navigation state unless the app architecture explicitly requires it.

## View Composition

- Keep views small and composable.
- Extract complex sections into separate views.
- Prefer modifiers over conditional branches when changing visual state to preserve view identity.
- Use stable identity in `ForEach`; do not use `.indices` for dynamic collections.
- Avoid `AnyView` in repeated rows or performance-sensitive views.
- Avoid object creation and expensive formatting in `body`.

## Modern APIs

- Use `foregroundStyle()` instead of `foregroundColor()`.
- Use `clipShape(.rect(cornerRadius:))` instead of `cornerRadius()`.
- Use `Button` instead of `onTapGesture()` unless gesture location/count is required.
- Use modern `onChange` variants with zero or two parameters.
- Use `.task` and `.task(id:)` for async work that should cancel automatically.
- Avoid `UIScreen.main.bounds` and fixed screen assumptions.
- Avoid `GeometryReader` unless no simpler layout API fits.

## Async and Concurrency

- Keep UI state updates on the main actor.
- Use structured concurrency.
- Do not launch untracked detached tasks from views.
- Cancel long-running work when views disappear or task inputs change.
- Surface async errors in UI state instead of silently swallowing them.

## Quality Gate

Before considering SwiftUI work complete:

- The app builds.
- New state flows have a real source of truth.
- Important user actions have loading, empty, and error states.
- Dynamic lists use stable identity.
- UI works in light/dark mode unless the product intentionally supports only one.
- Accessibility labels exist for icon-only controls.
